eground women in the life of Jesus Christ—including accounts of women at the Incarnation and the Tomb—and in Scripture in general. Tatlock’s selections give the modern reader a sense of the structure and nature of Catharina’s devotional writings, highlighting the alternative they offer to the male-centered view of early modern literary and cultural production during her day, and redefining the role of women in Christian history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aIncarnationvMeditations. 0aIncarnationxMeditations. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  acatharina regina von greiffenberg, religion, spirituality, christianity, catholicism, religious women, nonfiction, faith, devotional, germany, female poet, gender, meditations, jesus christ, scripture, incarnation, tomb, virgin mary, passion, crucifixion, holiness, salvation, praise, worship, bible, prayer, redemption, resurrection.1 aKing, Margaret L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabil, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTatlock, Lynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTatlock, Lynne.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022686487740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226864907423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226864907/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles